---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About — Mission Sikhism"
  description="A non-profit, community-built, fully-sourced history of the Sikh faith — and how to contribute to it."
>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container about">
      <h1>About</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        Mission Sikhism is a non-profit, community-built history of the Sikh
        faith, from 1469 to today — offered freely, without paywalls, in the
        spirit of <em>sarbat da bhala</em>, the welfare of all.
      </p>

      <h2>Our one promise</h2>
      <p>
        Sikh history is often retold without references. This site takes the
        opposite approach: <strong>every factual claim is tied to a citation</strong>,
        and that rule is enforced by the build itself. A page physically cannot
        publish if any of its content lacks a source — the guarantee is checked by
        software, not left to memory. You can see the result on the
        <a href="/library">Library</a> page, which gathers every source cited
        across the whole site into one bibliography.
      </p>

      <h2>How the site is built</h2>
      <p>
        The history is organised three ways over one set of facts: as a
        <a href="/history">timeline</a>, as an interactive <a href="/map">map</a>
        where every event is placed where it happened, and as the
        <a href="/people">people</a> who shaped it. Alongside sit
        <a href="/faith">The Faith</a> and <a href="/culture">Culture &amp;
        Heritage</a>. It is a static, open project — plain text files in a public
        repository — so it is fast, durable, and free to run.
      </p>

      <h2 id="contribute">Contribute</h2>
      <p>
        This project grows as research grows, and it is better for more eyes. If
        you have spotted an inaccuracy, found a stronger source, or know of an
        event not yet documented, we would like to hear from you.
      </p>
      <p>
        There is one condition, and it is the same one the whole site runs on:
        <strong>include a reference</strong>. Every suggestion should come with a
        verifiable source — a book with its author and page, or a link — so a
        maintainer can check and credit it before it goes live. Contributions
        without a source cannot be published, however well-intentioned.
      </p>

      <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>

      <h3>Why is everything sourced?</h3>
      <p>
        Because trust is the point. A history that cannot be checked is just a
        story. Requiring a citation for every claim keeps the site honest and lets
        readers follow any fact back to where it comes from.
      </p>

      <h3>How is the history divided?</h3>
      <p>
        Into six eras, from Guru Nanak in 1469 to the present day. The framing is
        meant to be clear and faithful to the tradition; if you think an era is
        drawn wrongly, that is exactly the kind of feedback we welcome.
      </p>

      <h3>Who is behind it?</h3>
      <p>
        It is a volunteer, non-profit effort, dedicated to Waheguru and offered as
        a free resource for study, practice and research.
      </p>

      <h3>Can I reuse the content?</h3>
      <p>
        The site is intended as a free educational resource. Full licensing
        details will be published here.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
